
There are 2 major types of relationships between the control voltage and the audio output:

\begin{itemize}
    \item
          Linear to exponential relationship: a linear voltage produces and exponential
          change in the signal frequency, for example

          \begin{table}[ht]
              \centering

              \begin{tabular}{| c | c |}
                  \hline
                  CV in & Frequency out \\
                  \hline
                  $1 V$ & $55 Hz$       \\
                  $2 V$ & $110 Hz$      \\
                  $3 V$ & $220 Hz$      \\
                  $4 V$ & $440 Hz$      \\
                  $5 V$ & $880 Hz$      \\
                  $6 V$ & $1760 Hz$     \\
                  \hline
              \end{tabular}

              \caption{Exponential relationship}
              \label{exponential-relationship}
          \end{table}

          where an increment of $1 Volt$ doubles the output frequency.
    \item
          Linear to linear relationship: a linear voltage produces a linear change in the
          signal frequency, for example

          \begin{table}[ht]
              \centering

              \begin{tabular}{| c | c |}
                  \hline
                  CV in & Frequency out \\
                  \hline
                  $1 V$ & $55 Hz$       \\
                  $2 V$ & $110 Hz$      \\
                  $3 V$ & $165 Hz$      \\
                  $4 V$ & $220 Hz$      \\
                  $5 V$ & $275 Hz$      \\
                  $6 V$ & $330 Hz$      \\
                  \hline
              \end{tabular}

              \caption{Linear relationship}
              \label{linear-relationship}
          \end{table}

          where an increment of $1 Volt$ moves the output frequency of the fixed value of
          $55Hz$.
\end{itemize}

Since the human ear perceives sound logarithmicly, we will choose a linear to exponential
relationship, more precisely, the frequency should double with a $1 V$ input increment
as seen in Table \ref{exponential-relationship}.
